{"title_page": "Corinna Putnam Smith", "text_new": "{{short description|American archaeologist}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n'''Corinna Putnam Smith''' (born '''Corinna Haven Putnam''', September 27, 1876, New York \u2013 died 1965) was an American writer, amateur [[archaeologist]], scholar of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Islam]], and an [[activist]]. After the death of her husband in 1950, she adopted his middle name, calling herself '''Corinna Lindon Smith'''.<ref name=SNAC />\n\n==Life==\nCorinna was the daughter of the [[publisher]] [[George Haven Putnam]].<ref name=SNAC>[http://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6208fq8 Corinna Haven (Putnam) Smith, 1876\u20131965], [[SNAC]].</ref> \nIn 1898 she met the [[painter]] [[Joseph Lindon Smith]] whom she married in 1899. Together, they spent many winters on archaeological sites in Egypt, while the summer months saw them hosting large social events in [[Dublin, New Hampshire]], attended by the likes of [[Mark Twain]] and [[John Singer Sargent]].<ref name=SNAC /><ref name=Larkin>Diana Wolfe Larkin, [http://www.monadnockart.org/artists-past/joseph-lindon-smith Joseph Lindon Smith \u2013 Interpreter of the Past (1863\u20131950)], 2008, Monadnock Art.</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Rising Above the Ruins in France: An Account of the Progress Made Since the Armistice in the Devastated Regions in Reestablishing Industrial Activities and the Normal Life of the People'', New York and London, [[G.P. Putnam's Sons]] 1920 (with Caroline R. Hill)\n*(Editor of:) Joseph Lindon Smith, ''Tombs, Temples, and Ancient Art'', [[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman]], [[University of Oklahoma Press]] 1956\n*''Interesting People: Eighty Years With the Great and Near Great'', Norman, University of Oklahoma Press 1962\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-archaeologist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American archaeologist}}\n{{refimprove|date=April 2019}}\n\n'''Corinna Putnam Smith''' (born '''Corinna Haven Putnam''', September 27, 1876, New York \u2013 died 1965) was an American writer, amateur [[archaeologist]], scholar of [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Islam]], and an [[activist]]. After the death of her husband in 1950, she adopted his middle name, calling herself '''Corinna Lindon Smith'''.<ref name=SNAC />\n\n==Life==\nCorinna was the daughter of the [[publisher]] [[George Haven Putnam]].<ref name=SNAC>[http://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6208fq8 Corinna Haven (Putnam) Smith, 1876\u20131965], [[SNAC]].</ref> \nIn 1898 she met the [[painter]] [[Joseph Lindon Smith]] whom she married in 1899. Together, they spent many winters on archaeological sites in Egypt, while the summer months saw them hosting large social events in [[Dublin, New Hampshire]], attended by the likes of [[Mark Twain]] and [[John Singer Sargent]].<ref name=SNAC /><ref name=Larkin>Diana Wolfe Larkin, [http://www.monadnockart.org/artists-past/joseph-lindon-smith Joseph Lindon Smith \u2013 Interpreter of the Past (1863\u20131950)], 2008, Monadnock Art.</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Rising Above the Ruins in France: An Account of the Progress Made Since the Armistice in the Devastated Regions in Reestablishing Industrial Activities and the Normal Life of the People'', New York and London, [[G.P. Putnam's Sons]] 1920 (with Caroline R. Hill)\n*(Editor of:) Joseph Lindon Smith, ''Tombs, Temples, and Ancient Art'', [[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman]], [[University of Oklahoma Press]] 1956\n*''Interesting People: Eighty Years With the Great and Near Great'', Norman, University of Oklahoma Press 1962\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-archaeologist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corinna_Putnam_Smith"}
{"title_page": "Cookie Lommel", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Cookie Lommel\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]], U.S.\n| occupation = Writer, biographer, film producer, activist\n| spouse = [[Ulli Lommel]]\n}}\n'''Cookie Lommel''' (born 1970) is an American author, biographer, film producer, and activist.\n\n==Early life==\nCookie Lommel was born in [[Cleveland, Ohio]].<ref name=LAT /> She began her career in the entertainment industry in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/cashbox55unse_14|title=Cash Box|date=30 November 1991|publisher=Cash Box Pub. Co.|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Early on she worked as a journalist for ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'' magazine and ''[[Radio & Records]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=_ft6SOIW0l0C&pg=PA4|title=Robert Church|first=Cookie|last=Lommel|date=13 October 1995|publisher=Holloway House Publishing|via=Google Books|isbn=9780870677892}}</ref> She has also worked as an entertainment industry reporter at [[CNN]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/archives/a-jewish-connection---in-her-soul-and-in/article_fcaa9c58-da7a-5e98-9e23-eee8e1d5a735.html|title=A Jewish connection - in her soul and in her jobs|first=CYNTHIA DETTELBACH|last=Editor|publisher=}}</ref> and as entertainment editor at ''[[Teen Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=4laORCuvf9UC&pg=PA104|title=Russell Simmons|first1=Cookie|last1=Lommel|first2=Chuck|last2=D|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Infobase Publishing|via=Google Books|isbn=9781438103518}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nIn 2003, she was named the executive director of the [[Jewish Labor Committee]]'s Western region.<ref name=LAT /> Prior to this, in 1992 Lommel founded Operation Unity,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9511/operation_unity/|title=CNN - Teen-agers find new direction - Nov. 10, 1995|website=www.cnn.com}}</ref> a non-profit organization that funded the travel of inner city minority students to live on an Israeli [[Kibbutz]].<ref name=LAT>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/mar/14/entertainment/ca-tugend14|title=One-woman bridge|first=Tom|last=Tugend|date=14 March 2004|publisher=|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n\n==Author==\nCookie Lommel authored the 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/print/20001211/25180-african-american-children-s-books.html|title=African-American Children's Books|publisher=}}</ref> book ''The History of Rap Music'',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kbE9uQLacRcC&pg=PA21|title=Sean Combs|first=Dale Evva|last=Gelfand|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Infobase Publishing|via=Google Books|isbn=9781438103525}}</ref> and ''Black Filmmakers'' in 2002.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=UZx2AwAAQBAJ&pg=PT361|title=Encyclopedia of African American Society|first=Gerald D.|last=Jaynes|date=1 February 2005|publisher=SAGE Publications|via=Google Books|isbn=9781452265414}}</ref> She is also the author of unauthorized biographies for [[Russell Simmons]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=0zPg7Cidoy0C&pg=PP47|title=The Hip-Hop Scene: The Stars, the Fans, the Music|first1=Ann Graham|last1=Gaines|first2=Reggie|last2=Majors|date=1 July 2009|publisher=Enslow Publishing, LLC|via=Google Books|isbn=9780766033962}}</ref> [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=A_1Oalp0qQEC&pg=PA162|title=Pro\u010d jsou \u00fasp\u011b\u0161n\u00ed lid\u00e9 \u00fasp\u011b\u0161n\u00ed|first=Rainer|last=Zitelmann|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Grada Publishing a.s.|via=Google Books|isbn=9788024741871}}</ref> [[James Oglethorpe]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=8rA1kYgFx-wC&pg=PA43|title=Heroes & Helpers Adventure Diaries-#6 Hannah, the Humanitarian Aid Worker!|first=Carole|last=Marsh|date=1 November 2003|publisher=Gallopade International|via=Google Books|isbn=9780635011534}}</ref> [[Johnnie L. Cochran]], Jr., [[Arthur Miller]],<ref name=LAT /> [[Robert Reed Church|Robert Church]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=9ZMt670GeGoC&pg=PA168|title=Fight On!: Mary Church Terrell's Battle for Integration|first1=Dennis B.|last1=Fradin|first2=Judith Bloom|last2=Fradin|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|via=Google Books|isbn=978-0618133499}}</ref> Madame [[C.J. Walker]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=A5Y5Kk12xkkC&pg=PA103|title=Madam C.J. Walker: Entrepreneur and Millionaire|first=Darlene R.|last=Stille|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Capstone|via=Google Books|isbn=9780756518837}}</ref> [[Michelle Pfeiffer]],<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=ZHrEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23 |title = Wie w\u00fcrde Johnny Depp pr\u00e4sentieren?: Was Sie von Schauspielern f\u00fcr Ihren Vortrag lernen k\u00f6nnen|isbn = 9783864146237|last1 = L\u00fcder|first1 = Peter|date = 2014-02-14}}</ref> and [[Mary Church Terrell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=LBXl8aueRisC&pg=PA126|title=Study Guide for Let Nobody Turn Us Around|first1=Karen G.|last1=Williams|first2=Andrea|last2=Queeley|date=13 October 2018|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe was married to actor and film director [[Ulli Lommel]] between 1988 and his death in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=HMpZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT260|title=Obituaries in the Performing Arts, 2017|first=Harris M. Lentz|last=III|date=30 April 2018|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lommel, Cookie}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American music journalists]]\n[[Category:American biographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cleveland]]\n[[Category:American magazine writers]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Music historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Cookie Lommel\n|